 bodies as a site of struggle for autonomy, she created a discursive space for women to engage in the public sphere and act as sexual agents. In turn, her ideas contributed to the rise of a feminist consciousness that recognized the personal as political and rejected dualistic notions of gender and sex.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFeministsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aFeministszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJewish anarchistsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aJewish anarchistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen anarchistsxBiographyxUnited States. 0aWomen anarchistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen and socialismxUnited StatesxBiography. 0aWomen and socialism. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : History. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438459752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438459752/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles